</figure>
<p data-index="584">Sometimes, a company sells a held-to-maturity debt security so close to its maturity date that a change in the market interest rate would not significantly affect the security's fair value. Such a sale may be considered a sale at maturity and would not call into question the company's original intent to hold the investment to maturity. Let's assume, as an example, that Robinson Company sells its investment in Evermaster bonds on November&nbsp;1, 2023, at&nbsp;99<span class="sup" data-index="585">¾</span> plus accrued interest. The discount amortization from July&nbsp;1, 2023, to November 1, 2023, is $635 (<math alttext="mathml" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" overflow="scroll" data-index="586"><mfrac bevelled="true" data-index="587"><mn data-index="588">4</mn><mn data-index="589">6</mn></mfrac></math> $952). Robinson records this discount amortization as follows.</p>
